There are multiple ways for doing this but I think in your case you first want to parse your example proto file to extract the features to be passed as tensors to your function. 

A starting point for parsing is the set of protos available in [TFJava](https://github.com/tensorflow/java/tree/master/tensorflow-core/tensorflow-core-api/src/gen/java/org/tensorflow/proto/example). Once you get hold on a list of values (such as a `FloatList`), you can create a tensor from it or by passing that list as an array of bytes to this [factory](https://github.com/tensorflow/java/blob/a4e79643fd734033e000ecd6b9b0c4644440ce7e/tensorflow-core/tensorflow-core-api/src/main/java/org/tensorflow/Tensor.java#L184).

For example this converts the Int64List `input` feature to a vector:
```java
    Example example = Example.parseFrom(new FileInputStream(&quot;your_example.pb&quot;));
    Feature feature = example.getFeatures().getFeatureOrThrow(&quot;input&quot;);
    long[] values = feature.getInt64List().getValueList().stream().mapToLong(i -&gt; i.longValue()).toArray();
    try (TInt64 tensor = TInt64.vectorOf(values)) {
      System.out.println(&quot;Tensor shape is &quot; + tensor.shape());
    }
```

There are several options to stream data from the server
 - Server-sent events pushing individual events (media type: `text/event-stream`)
 - Streaming events separated by newlines (media type: `application/x-ndjson`)

You could deserialize json entry `DataEntry` and the `filter`

For example for `application/x-ndjson`

```
webclient.get()
   .uri(URL)
   .accept(APPLICATION_NDJSON)
   .retrieve()
   .bodyToFlux(DataEntry.class)
   .filter(entry -&gt; entry.getIndex() % 2 == 0);
```

for SSE just set `.accept(TEXT_EVENT_STREAM)`


**UPDATE**

For &quot;classic&quot; json array response. Not sure what exactly you want to filter out but, `bodyToFlux` should handle it if json is valid. Here is a complete test using wiremock


```
@Test
void test() {
    String data = &quot;&quot;&quot;
            [
            {
            &quot;key&quot;: &quot;key1&quot;
            },
            {
            &quot;key&quot;: &quot;key2&quot;
            },
            {
            &quot;key&quot;: &quot;key3&quot;
            }
            ]
            &quot;&quot;&quot;;

    stubFor(get(&quot;/test&quot;)
            .willReturn(aResponse()
                    .withHeader(HttpHeaders.CONTENT_TYPE, MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON_VALUE)
                    .withStatus(200)
                    .withBody(data)
            )
    );

    WebClient webClient = WebClient.create(&quot;http://localhost:&quot; + wireMockServer.port());

    Flux&lt;DataEntry&gt; res = webClient.get()
            .uri(&quot;/test&quot;)
            .retrieve()
            .bodyToFlux(DataEntry.class);

    StepVerifier.create(res)
            .expectNext(new DataEntry(&quot;key1&quot;))
            .expectNext(new DataEntry(&quot;key2&quot;))
            .expectNext(new DataEntry(&quot;key3&quot;))
            .verifyComplete();
}
```


ps

you don&#39;t need to apply `try-catch` to reactive sequence and typically you don&#39;t need to `subscribe` explicitly

