According to https://stackoverflow.com/questions/56834141/how-to-remove-selected-elements-from-a-combobox I had to use `Platform.runLater()` in order to make sure that the property change is dealt with before doing anything with the selection. This is the working code:

```java
    @FXML
    private void selectRol(ActionEvent event) {
    	Rol selected = rollenDropdown.getSelectionModel().getSelectedItem();
    	if (selected != null) {
    		Platform.runLater(() -&gt; {
    			rollenDropdown.setValue(null);
            	rollenDropdown.getItems().remove(selected);
    		});
    	}
    }
```

If you are concerned about the unspecified time at which Platform.runLater executes the action, you can try the below approach.

This approach is effectively using the [AnimationTimer](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/api/javafx/animation/AnimationTimer.html) to run the desired actions at the end of the current pulse. 

Considering its possible performance issues (mentioned in the [doc](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/api/javafx/application/Platform.html#runLater-java.lang.Runnable-)),I would prefer to use Platform.runLater only in multi threading situations.

    @FXML
    private void selectRol(ActionEvent event) {
        Rol selected = rollenDropdown.getSelectionModel().getSelectedItem();
        if (selected != null) {
            doEndOfPulse(() -&gt; {
                rollenDropdown.setValue(null);
                rollenDropdown.getItems().remove(selected);
            });
        }
    }
    
    /**
     * Executes the provided runnable at the end of the current pulse.
     *
     * @param runnable runnable to execute
     */
    public static void doEndOfPulse(final Runnable runnable) {
        new AnimationTimer() {
    
            @Override
            public void handle(final long now) {
                runnable.run();
                stop();
            }
        }.start();
    }

